RELATIONSHIPS DIAGRAM
================================================================================

users
  ├─ listings (one user has many listings)
  ├─ bids (one user places many bids)
  ├─ conversations (one user has many conversations)
  ├─ messages (one user sends many messages)
  ├─ reviews_given (one user writes many reviews)
  ├─ reviews_received (one user receives many reviews)
  ├─ trade_offers (one user makes many trade offers)
  ├─ watchlist (one user favorites many listings)
  └─ refresh_tokens (one user has many tokens)

listings
  ├─ bids (one listing has many bids)
  ├─ conversations (one listing may have many conversations about it)
  ├─ reviews (one listing may have reviews)
  ├─ trade_offers (one listing receives many trade offers)
  └─ watchlist (one listing is favorited by many users)

conversations
  └─ messages (one conversation has many messages)


================================================================================
NOTES FOR IMPLEMENTATION
================================================================================

1. Use PostgreSQL (already configured in your .env)

2. Use Prisma ORM - easier to manage migrations
   Command: npx prisma migrate dev --name add_all_tables

3. All IDs should be UUID for security (harder to guess than integers)

4. All foreign keys should have ON DELETE CASCADE or SET NULL:
   - CASCADE: When parent is deleted, delete child records
   - SET NULL: When parent is deleted, set foreign key to null

5. Add indexes on frequently queried columns:
   - All foreign keys
   - listingType, status (for filtering)
   - createdAt (for sorting)

6. String arrays (images, offeredCards) are natively supported in PostgreSQL

7. Default values prevent null issues:
   - rating = 0
   - totalReviews = 0
   - bidCount = 0
   - views = 0
   - watchers = 0

8. Timestamps (createdAt, updatedAt) automatically managed by Prisma


